[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Comment Quality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Comments are excellent throughout. They explain:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Why federation uses parallel dispatch (network latency is the bottleneck)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Why each institution has its own Lambda adapter (cross-account isolation)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Why authorization is checked twice (defense in depth for PHI-derived knowledge)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Why the ontology mapping cache exists and its limitations (TTL needed in production)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Why `InvocationType="RequestResponse"` is used (synchronous because we need results)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Why Neptune must be in a VPC (no public endpoint)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Why `ThreadPoolExecutor` works for this use case (I/O-bound, not CPU-bound)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - What consensus_score means and when it's null (single source can't calculate)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Why the sharing policy check is attribute-based (ABAC for knowledge-level access)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The opening disclaimer is well-calibrated: it positions the code as "the technical skeleton, not the finished building" and explicitly calls out governance as the hard part.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Logical Flow
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The code reads top-to-bottom in a pedagogically sound order:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. Configuration and constants (infrastructure endpoints, timeouts)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. Source registration (onboarding an institution)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. Ontology mapping (the translation layer)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 4. Query translation (rewriting for local schemas)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 5. Source discovery (finding who to ask)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 6. Federated execution (the orchestrator)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 7. Remote invocation (calling another institution)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 8. Local adapter (what runs at each institution)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 9. Result assembly (merging and deduplication)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 10. Full pipeline demo (putting it together)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 11. Gap to production (honest assessment)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This matches the natural mental model of "set up the network, then run a query through it." The decision to show registration first (Steps 1-2) before query execution (Steps 3-8) is good pedagogy because it establishes the infrastructure before showing how queries flow through it.
